<subSubSection id="A0E565E2FF87FFFBFEEE1B77847CB128" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="E8403669FF87FFFBFEEE1B7786F8B39E" blockId="16.[375,940,378,405]" box="[375,940,378,405]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815">
<heading id="B3088105FF87FFFBFEEE1B7786F8B39E" box="[375,940,378,405]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" reason="5">
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF87FFFBFEEE1B7786F8B39E" authority="(Guerin-Meneville, 1855)" baseAuthorityName="Guerin-Meneville" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[375,940,378,405]" class="Malacostraca" family="Atyidae" genus="Xiphocaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongata">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF87FFFBFEEE1B778722B39E" bold="true" box="[375,630,378,405]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="815">Xiphocaris elongata</emphasis>
(Guérin-Méneville, 1855)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF87FFFBFF591BA2847CB128" blockId="16.[160,1156,431,803]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815">
This atyid shrimp was the most encountered decapod in St. Thomas ghuts during August but was absent in November. We found it in Dorothea, Flamboyan, and Neltjeberg ghuts, from 20 to +200 metres above sea level. Above 100 metres, it was always in high densities in pools between riffles, often with as many as 50 per square metre. The shrimp was always far more apparent and active at night, and its eyes reflected the light of our headlamps. This shrimp actively grazes on periphyton, leaf litter, and insect larvae (
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF87FFFBFBA51850840BB092" author="March JG &amp; Pringle CM" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" pagination="84 - 93" refId="ref26642" refString="March JG, Pringle CM. 2003. Food web structure and basal resource utilization along a tropical island stream continuum, Puerto Rico. Biotropica. 35 (1): 84 - 93. doi: 10.1111 / j. 1744 - 7429.2003. tb 00265. x." type="journal article" year="2003">March and Pringle 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF87FFFBFEF2188D872FB092" author="Wright MS &amp; Covich AP" box="[363,635,640,665]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" pagination="536 - 546" refId="ref31987" refString="Wright MS, Covich AP. 2005. Relative importance of bacteria and fungi in a tropical headwater stream: leaf decomposition and invertebrate feeding preference. Microb Ecol. 49 (4): 536 - 546. doi: 10.1007 / s 00248 - 004 - 0052 - 4." type="journal article" year="2005">Wright and Covich 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF87FFFBFD1E188D8610B092" author="Crowl TA &amp; Welsh V &amp; Heartsill-Scalley T &amp; Covich AP" box="[647,836,640,665]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" pagination="198 - 208" refId="ref23860" refString="Crowl TA, Welsh V, Heartsill-Scalley T, Covich AP. 2006. Effects of different types of conditioning on rates of leaf-litter shredding by Xiphocaris elongata, a Neotropical freshwater shrimp. J North Am Benthol Soc. 25 (1): 198 - 208. doi: 10.1899 / 0887 - 3593 (2006) 25 [198: EODTOC] 2.0. CO; 2." type="journal article" year="2006">Crowl et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). During the day 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF87FFFBFB91188D81D0B092" baseAuthorityName="Guerin-Meneville" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[1032,1156,640,665]" class="Malacostraca" family="Atyidae" genus="Xiphocaris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongata">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF87FFFBFB91188D81D0B092" box="[1032,1156,640,665]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="815">X. elongata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be seen moving about in full sunlight, grazing across the larger rocks and woody debris. 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF87FFFBFF6B18C884D2B0D5" author="Beatty HA" box="[242,390,709,734]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" pagination="261 - 268" refId="ref22509" refString="Beatty HA. 1968. A checklist of Crustacea of St. Croix, Virgin Islands. J Agric Univ Puerto Rico. 52: 261 - 268. doi: 10.46429 / jaupr. v 52 i 3.11514." type="journal article" year="1968">Beatty (1968)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF87FFFBFE2618C88785B0D5" author="Chase FA &amp; Hobbs HH" box="[447,721,709,734]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" pagination="1 - 245" refId="ref23476" refString="Chase FA, Hobbs HH. 1969. The freshwater and terrestrial decapod crustaceans of the West Indies, with special reference to Dominica. U S Natl Mus Bull. 292: 1 - 245. doi: 10.5479 / si. 03629236.292.1." type="journal article" year="1969">Chase and Hobbs (1969)</bibRefCitation>
report this species from St. Croix, with 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF87FFFBFF3918E584C4B10A" author="Nemeth D &amp; Platenberg R &amp; Mathurin R &amp; Hodge D" box="[160,400,744,769]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" pagination="70 - 74" refId="ref27733" refString="Nemeth D, Platenberg R, Mathurin R, Hodge D. 2007. Impact of watershed development on diversity of freshwater fish and crustaceans on St. Thomas, US Virgin Islands. In: Hwang S, editor. Proc 7 th Caribbean Islands Water Resources Congress; Oct 25 - 26 2007; St. Croix, U. S. Virgin Islands. p. 70 - 74." type="book chapter" year="2007">Nemeth et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
reporting it from St. Thomas and 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF87FFFBFCB118E58117B10A" author="Perez-Reyes O &amp; Crowl TA &amp; Hernandez-Garcia PJ &amp; Ledesma-Fuste R &amp; Villar-Fornes FA &amp; Covich AP" box="[808,1091,744,769]" pageId="16" pageNumber="815" pagination="329 - 344" refId="ref28364" refString="Perez-Reyes O, Crowl TA, Hernandez-Garcia PJ, Ledesma-Fuste R, Villar-Fornes FA, Covich AP. 2013. Freshwater decapods of Puerto Rico: a checklist and reports of new localities. Zootaxa. 3717 (3): 329 - 344. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3717.3.3." type="journal article" year="2013">Pérez-Reyes et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF87FFFBFF3919078470B128" box="[160,292,778,803]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="16" pageNumber="815">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
